\par INTRODUCTION.
\par IT would have been a bold step indeed for anyone, some
\par thirty years ago, to have thought of treating the public to a
\par collection of stones ordinarily reputed fabulous, and of claiming
\par for them the consideration due to genuine realities, or
\par to have advocated tales, time-honoured as fictions, as actual
\par facts ; and those of the nursery as being, in many instances,
\par legends, more or less distorted, descriptive of real beings or
\par events.
\par Now-a-days it is a less hazardous proceeding. The great
\par era of advanced opinion, initiated by Darwin, which has seen,
\par in the course of a few years, a larger progress in knowledge
\par in all departments of science than decades of centuries preceding
\par it, has, among other changes, worked a complete
\par revolution in the estimation of the value of folk-lore ; and
\par speculations on it, which in the days of our boyhood would
\par have been considered as puerile, are now admitted to be not
\par merely interesting but necessary to those who endeavour to
\par gather up the skeins of unwritten history, and to trace the
\par antecedents and early migrations from parent sources of
\par nations long since alienated from each other by customs,
\par speech, and space.
