\par I have, therefore, but little hesitation in gravely proposing
\par to submit that many of the so-called mythical animals, which
\par throughout long ages and in all nations have been the fertile
\par subjects of fiction and fable, come legitimately within the
\par scope of plain matter-of-fact Natural History, and that they
\par may be considered, not as the outcome of exuberant fancy,
\par but as creatures which really once existed, and of which,
\par unfortunately, only imperfect and inaccurate descriptions have
\par filtered down to us, probably very much refracted, through
\par the mists of time.
