\par THE reasoning upon the question whether dragons, winged
\par snakes, sea-serpents, unicorns, and other so-called fabulous
\par monsters have in reality existed, and at dates coeval with
\par man, diverges in several independent directions.
\par We have to consider :
\par 1. Whether the characters attributed to these creatures
\par are or are not so abnormal in comparison with those of known
\par types, as to render a belief in their existence impossible or
\par the reverse.
\par 2. Whether it is rational to suppose that creatures so
\par formidable, and apparently so capable of self-protection,
\par should disappear entirely, while much more defenceless
\par species continue to survive them.
\par 3. The myths, traditions, and historical allusions from
\par which their reality may be inferred require to be classified
\par and annotated, and full weight given to the evidence which
\par has accumulated of the presence of man upon the earth
\par during ages long prior to the historic period, and which
\par may have been ages of slowly progressive civilization, or
\par perhaps cycles of alternate light and darkness, of knowledge
\par and barbarism.
\par 4. Lastly, some inquiry may be made into the geographical
\par conditions obtaining at the time of their possible
\par existence.
