\par IN reviewing the past succession of different forms of ancient
\par life upon the globe, we are reminded of a series of dissolving
\par views, in which each species evolves itself by an imperceptible
\par gradation from some pre-existing one, arrives at its maximum
\par of individuality, and then slowly fades away, while another
\par type, either higher or lower, evolved in turn from it, emerges
\par from obscurity, and succeeds it on the field of view.
\par Specific individuality has in all cases a natural term, dependent
\par on physical causes, but that term is in many cases
\par abruptly anticipated by a combination of unfavourable conditions.
\par Alteration of climate, isolation by geological changes, such
\par as the submergence of continents and islands, and the competition
\par of other species, are among the causes which have
\par at all times operated towards its destruction ; while, since the
\par evolution of man, his agency, so far as we can judge by what
\par we know of his later history, has been especially active in
\par the same direction.
\par The limited distribution of many species, even when not
\par enforced by insular conditions, is remarkable, and, of course,
\par highly favourable to their destruction. A multiplicity of
\par examples are familiar to naturalists, and possibly not a
\par few may have attracted the attention of the ordinary observer.
