\par certain regions of it, and the names of Sedgwick, Murchison,
\par Jukes, Phillips, Lyell, and others became, and will remain,
\par inseparably associated with the history of those great divisions
\par of the materials of the earth's crust, which, under the
\par names of the Cambrian, Silurian, Devonian, Carboniferous,
\par and Tertiary formations, have become familiar to us.
\par In those days, when observations were limited to a comparatively
\par small area, the lines separating most of these
\par formations were supposed to be hard and definite ; forms of
\par life which characterized one, were presumed to have become
