\par THE CHINESE DRAGON.
\par WE now approach the consideration of a country in which
\par the belief in the existence of the dragon is thoroughly
\par woven into the life of the whole nation. Yet at the same
\par time it has developed into such a medley of mythology and
\par superstition as to materially strengthen our conviction of the
\par reality of the basis upon which the belief has been founded,
\par though it involves us in a mass of intricate perplexities in
\par connection with the determination of its actual period of
\par existence.
\par There is no country so conservative as China, no nation
\par which can boast of such high antiquity, as a collective people
\par permanently occupying the same regions, and preserving
\par records of their polity, manners, and surroundings from the
\par earliest date of their occupation of the territory which still
\par remains the centre of their civilization ; and there is none in
\par which dragon culture has been more persistently maintained
\par down to the present day.
\par Its mythologies, histories, religions, popular stories, and
\par proverbs, all teem with references to a mysterious being who
\par has a physical nature and spiritual attributes. Gifted with
\par an accepted form, which he has the supernatural power of
\par casting off for the assumption of others, he has the power
\par of influencing the weather, producing droughts or fertilizing
\par THE CHINESE DRAGON. 213
\par rains at pleasure, of raising tempests and allaying them.
\par Volumes could be compiled from the scattered legends which
\par everywhere abound relating to this subject ; but as they are,
\par for the most part, like our medieval legends, echoes of each
\par other, no useful purpose would be served by doing so, and I
\par therefore content myself with drawing, somewhat copiously,
\par from one or two of the chief sources of information.
\par As, however, Chinese literature is but little known or
